Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I would be fine leaving the range as proposed but as Hemanth pointed out there is clearly error a) in the commit message which state the range b) the same faulty range is being used in the ignore. Either we should just state that we will cover this range from swp to swa or we should include the whole range.Stating that we cover whole range while just covering small subset of it is misleading.

Patch Set 2:

I guess, I'm wondering if not having this has ever actually caused issues for people. As a vim user, I still don't see much value in this. In reality stuff like this should be covered by a global gitignore (instructions here: https://help.github.com/articles/ignoring-files/#create-a-global-gitignore)

Patch Set 2:

I think this is good to fix the original bug, which was having a .gitignore in the codebase that only specified .swp and not the range of swap files

Patch Set 2:

So covering *.swp will cover 99% of vim users. *.swo is the next most likely swap extension (usually when a *.swp already exists). That said, anything other than that should be the user's responsibility and I would hope that people aren't randomly doing `git add .` and that our review policies are stringent enough to prevent swap files from being committed. I would just be surprised to see it get so far as a swap file being added to a review. For what it's worth, I'm not sure the bug is exactly valid either given the how infrequent a problem this seems to be.
